the lawyer for a woman convicted of poisoning two 
people with cyanide said he wants a mistrial after a juror admitted 
settling an unrelated product contamination lawsuit shortly before 
the trial began 
us district judge william dwyer questioned jurors friday about 
whether they were improperly influenced during deliberations in the 
nations first deathbyproducttampering trial 
most of the questioning was directed at juror laurel holliday 
who has acknowledged being the lone holdout for stella nickells 
acquittal before switching her vote to guilty on monday the fifth 
day of deliberation 
mrs nickell 44 of auburn was convicted of five counts of 
contaminating overthecounter medicine capsules with cyanide they 
included two counts of spiking the excedrin capsules that killed 
her husband bruce nickell 52 and susan katherine snow 40 of 
auburn in june 1986 
she faces possible life imprisonment at a june 17 sentencing 
prosecutors said she killed her husband to collect 176000 in life 
insurance 
before a verdict was reached ms holliday told dwyer she had 
received an anonymous phone call the previous friday telling her 
mrs nickell had failed an fbi lie detector test that information 
was inadmissible at trial 
after the verdict it was revealed ms holliday had filed a 
lawsuit of her own last year in a contaminated product incident 
but had not mentioned that fact during jury selection 
ms holliday sued pepperidge farm inc after she bit into a 
goldfish cracker in july 1986 that she said contained an 
aspirinsubstitute pill the matter was settled out of court for 
500 less than two months prior to ms hollidays selection for 
mrs nickells jury 
ms holliday told dwyer she dismissed the anonymous call from 
her mind and judged the case on the facts she also said she did 
not mention her own lawsuit during jury selection because she did 
not think it was relevant 
ms holliday also said friday that during the trial she had 
talked with friends about writing an article about her jury 
experiences but did not discuss facts of the case 
after the unusual session friday defense lawyer thomas hillier 
