<TEXT>
business leaders and reagan 
administration officials are betting that democrats have worked too 
hard to fashion trade legislation to scuttle it after president 
reagans expected veto 
members of congress have put a great deal of work in this 
legislation and my judgment is that these persons will not wish to 
see the bill disappear us trade representative clayton k 
yeutter said friday they have a great deal of time effort 
energy and creativity invested in this piece of legislation 
yeutter said he expected the president to deliver his veto 
message to congress next week but he said he was optimistic about 
it not meaning the end of the threeyear effort to write the trade 
bill 
although not specifically mentioning house speaker jim wright 
dtexas by name yeutter noted that a provision repealing the 
windfall oil profits tax is dear to the hearts of texas legislators 
i suspect it will be particularly difficult for them to 
explain to texas constituents that they were willing to drop a 
piece of legislation so important to the state of texas he said 
yeutter spoke with reporters after addressing a private session 
of the business council 
composed of 61 chief executives of the nations largest 
corporations the council meets twice a year at the homestead a 
posh resort in the mountains of southwestern virginia 
reagan is vetoing the massive trade bill because of a provision 
that would require companies to give 60 days notice of plant 
closings and major layoffs 
the administration supports much of the 1000page bill but 
objects to the plantclosing provision which yeutter called 
onerous 
yeutter said the technical language of the provision would 
provide a field day for lawyers and a nightmare for american 
businessmen by providing a legal basis for challenging virtually 
every plant closing or layoff 
american express co chairman james d robinson iii one of the 
executives attending the retreat ending today acknowledged that a 
veto of the trade bill risked losing very constructive 
legislation but he said the business community is prepared to 
take that risk 
its been called simple plantclosing legislation well its 
10 sections and 56 subsections and inconsistent language he said 
the business executives in an economic report issued at the 
start of their conference predicted that last years record trade 
deficit of 1712 billion would drop below 150 billion this year 
but the forecast which reflects a consensus of the member 
companies chief economists said the reduction would not be enough 
to stem the fall of the dollar 
it said the dollar which has lost about half of its value 
against the japanese yen in two years would fall from its present 
level of 125 yen to about 115 yen by the end of 1989 
john s reed chairman of citicorp the nations largest bank 
holding company said a substantial improvement in the trade 
deficit was iminent because of the devalued dollar 
a weaker dollar improves us export prospects by lower the cost 
of us goods overseas 
there is a price at which the trade balance will turn around 
and most of us think were pretty close to it reed said 
generally the executives forecast painted a rosy picture of 
moderate economic growth manageable inflation and low unemployment 
it said growth as measured by the gross national product would 
be 24 percent this year down from 38 percent last year 
inflation of consumer prices was expected to be 39 percent this 
year down from 44 percent in 1987 unemployment now at 54 
percent should remain under 6 percent through 1989 the executives 
said 
