billig a commander in rank to be released from active duty said 
lt brian cullin a spokesman for the service 
he will be released without pension sometime next week 
cullin said 
cullin said the decision against an appeal was made by navy 
secretary william ball and the navys judge advocate general rear 
adm h don campbell 
billig 57 was convicted in early 1986 on charges of 
involuntary manslaughter and negligence in the deaths of three 
patients he was sentenced on march 3 1986 to four years in 
prison and last summer was rebuffed in his first bid for parole 
from fort leavenworth kan 
billigs case attracted extensive public attention in part 
because of the sensational nature of some of the charges it also 
prompted congressional reviews of military health care in general 
and several large monetary settlements between the government and 
relatives of billigs patients 
prosecutors described billig as an egocentric man nearly blind 
in one eye who hid his visual handicap and continued performing 
complex heart operations despite numerous warnings that he was 
killing patients 
the us navymarine corps court of military review concluded 
april 13 however the prosecution never showed that billigs 
surgical technique and conduct in the operating room were so out of 
line as to constitute criminal conduct 
the spokesman said 36 legal claims totaling 1536 million were 
ultimately filed against the navy in connection with cases handled 
by billig to date 12 have been settled for a combined 22 
million eight denied and 16 are pending cullin said 
after reviewing the opinion the judge advocate general 
has determined there is no viable legal basis for further 
review ball said in a statement 
