he was skeptical at first a little suspicious 
not sure what to make of grass or trees or sunshine after all 
he hadnt seen those things in 27 years since he was 3 years old 
but willie b zoo atlantas star attraction quickly grew on 
friday to like his new home a 45 million outdoor rain 
forest where finally he will live like the western lowland 
gorilla he is 
as several dozen reporters photographers and zoo staffers 
watched from behind trees and bushes and across protective moats 
willie b played his part perfectly at what was a comingout both 
for him and for the oncebeleaguered zoo where he lives 
just four years ago the zoo was declared one of the worst in the 
nation by the humane society of the united states 
friday morning as only a few zoo employees quietly watched 
willie stepped out of his badweather shelter walked around felt 
rain and ran back in 
a very intelligent thing to do pronounced a proud zoo 
atlanta director terry maple 
later the door again was thrown open and the great ape hopped 
out to meet his public 
a minute later he climbed back in 
another minute later out again six minutes after that a car 
horn sounded and he scampered back inside 
all the while his eyes darted back and forth alert to the 
slightest movement or sound 
but after 40 minutes willie boldly climbed a small hill outside 
his door and picked up a few pieces of fruit thrown by his keeper 
he heard peacocks zoo construction trucks an airplane and car 
horns 
and for the first time in 27 years he felt the sunshine on his 
back 
within an hour he was jumping in the air trying to delimb his 
first tree 
the zoo director beamed 
this is a very special moment maple said i will always 
treasure this time im delighted with the way he responded to 
the whole thing it just couldnt have been better 
willie b named for former longtime atlanta mayor william b 
hartsfield last month was moved from his tilewalled steelbarred 
cage his home since he arrived at the zoo in may 1961 into the 
new indoor quarters he will use for sleep and shelter 
after five weeks to grow accustomed to the enclosure with 
charles horton his keeper of 14 years often sleeping nearby to 
keep him company zoo officials decided he was ready 
soon he will live near but separated from 13 gorillas on 
loan from emory universitys yerkes primate research center 
zoo officials hope that within a year willie can go on a date 
well get a young reproductiveproven female hopefully one 
who could be seductive and friendly said yerkes director 
frederick king a marilyn monroe of gorillas to show him what to 
do 
</TEXT>
