central committees propaganda department also provided casualty 
figures to foreign reporters covering the pullout which is to 
begin sunday 
in moscow the official tass news agency reported that the blast 
killed 11 people and wounded 13 and blamed afghan antigovernment 
formations 
the explosion demolished embankment walls on both sides of the 
river which threads through this ancient capital city whose 
streets are now filled with soviet troops tanks and armored 
personnel carriers 
blood was visible on the gates of a nearby factory and personal 
belongings including carpet slippers were scattered in the street 
witnesses said flames were visible when they arrived shortly 
after the blast the bomb had been planted in a large truck that 
was badly mangled 
last month six people were killed and 49 wounded in another 
bomb blast along the river banks on the 10th anniversary of the 
april 1978 revolution that brought a marxist government to power 
and triggered widespread insurrection 
anticommunist guerrillas also were blamed for a may 4 attack on 
a soviet convoy north of kabul that killed a photographer for the 
soviet newspaper izvestia and an undisclosed number of soldiers it 
also wounded sevruks son who also works for izvestia 
soviet troops entered afghanistan in december 1979 to help the 
sovietallied government put down the insurrection 
about 115000 soviets have been assisting najibs troops but 
they will begin leaving the country on sunday in observance of a 
peace agreement signed in geneva on april 14 
half of the soviets must be out by aug 15 and the rest are 
expected to follow quickly although the accord gives them nine 
months to complete the pullout 
at a new conference today the head of the soviet military 
contingent in afghanistan said the guerrilas were taking their toll 
on soviet and afghan troops but that rebel attacks would not deter 
the withdrawal 
the opposition may have some effect on us but not much and 
certainly they will not be able to frustrate the timetable lt 
gen boris gromov told reporters 
troops manning the soviet armor in kabul have been setting out 
gasoline pumps and supplies along the route of retreat for 
security reasons soviet officials have been tightlipped about the 
exact number of troops who will begin the move north on sunday 
the soviet national news program vremya reported friday night 
that soldiers were ready for the withdrawal but gave no figures 
vremya reported that 167 soviet encampments would be left behind 
for the afghans to use but that some of the facilities would be 
put to civilian use as hospitals and schools 
information for this account was based in part on a news agency 
pool report from kabul by reuters and on moscow monitoring of 
soviet news broadcasts the associated press was not allowed to go 
on the trip to kabul because of questions it asked najib in the 
capital last month 
