<DOCNO> AP880514-0093 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the defense department in a surprise move 
has settled a lawsuit brought by two environmental groups by 
agreeing to sharply curtail research into a highpower electrical 
phenomenon known as electromagnetic pulse 
the settlement approved by us district judge john garrett 
penn late friday derails at least temporarily a program the 
pentagon had previously described as crucial to national security 
among other purposes the research involved ways to harden 
crucial commnications and weapons guidance equipment against 
electrical surges triggered by nuclear explosions 
the defense department must now determine whether its 
experiments involving simulations powered by nonnuclear means 
pose a danger to humans or wildlife 
jeremy rifkin the president of the foundation on economic 
trends one of the environmental groups which filed the lawsuit 
hailed the agreement as the first court victory of this magnitude 
recognizing the threat posed by electronic or electrical 
pollution 
were extremely pleased rifkin added this is the first 
recognition by the defense department and really the first on a 
national level at all of a whole new environmental hazard facing 
all of us 
the pentagon declined to discuss the matter or its reasons for 
settling the case 
the suit filed in march 1987 by the washingtonbased foundation 
and the potomac river association inc sought essentially 
exactly what we got an end to highpower testing until an 
assessment is performed of the threat to the environment and human 
and animal health rifkin said 
the settlement will shut down or sharply curtail the operations 
of a handful of army and navy generators and potentially one air 
force facility 
electromagnetic pulse or emp is a powerful wave or surge of 
electrical energy that is released by a nuclear explosion and which 
can travel long distances through the atmosphere or water 
emp became a matter of concern to the military in the early 
1960s when the pentagon discovered a nuclear bomb detonated at high 
altitudes could generate a pulse so strong it could disable the 
electronic components used in computers communications and 
guidance equipment 
as a result of that discovery military laboratories have 
studied the phenomenon for 25 years in the course of developing 
methods for enabling electronic weapons components to withstand emp 
in recent years emp work also has been performed with an eye 
toward harnessing the energy pulses for offensive weapons or zap 
guns 
under the terms of the settlement the army must now shut down 
emp generators located at woodbridge va redstone arsenal ala 
and white sands missile range nm 
the navy will be required to shut down its socalled empress 1 
generator at the patuxent naval air station md to refrain from 
starting construction of an empress 2 system and to significantly 
reduce the operating power of two other patuxent generators 
the air force meantime will be allowed to continue operating 
emp simulators at kirtland air force base nm but only if it can 
provide documentation within 14 days demonstrating there is no 
discernible environmental risk from that operation 
rick garcia public affairs director for the air force weapons 
laboratory at kirtland said we would be prepared to furnish 
the documentation one of the five emp simulators at kirtland is 
one dubbed trestle a 58 million structure which enables 
scientists to imitate emp effects upon aircraft electrical 
equipment 
the other emp facilities which are located in closer proximity 
to populated areas must remain shut down or operating only at low 
power levels until an environmental assessment of their operation 
is conducted rifkin said 
the assessment probably will take five to six months at which 
point all the generators may be returned to service but only at 
reduced power levels that ensure no electrical surge moves beyond 
the boundaries of the bases 
the pentagon must then satisfactorily complete a fullfledged 
environmental impact study a process that could take two years 
before the emp generators can be used at their current power 
levels rifkin said 
while the pentagon declined comment rifkin said he thought the 
government agreed to settle the case because the foundations 
attorneys learned that two army employees had warned the service 
against conducting emp experiments at woodbridge until an 
environmental assessment was completed 
when the foundation filed a motion to question the two workers 
pentagon and justice department lawyers suddenly indicated a 
willingness to negotiate rifkin continued 
they didnt want these guys to talk about the hazards he 
said we had them over a barrel 
the foundations lawsuit asserted that emp experiments can 
affect human health directly and through the disruption of 
electronic circuits in nuclear power plants automobiles 
computers airplanes phone lines and navigational systems can 
cause potential catastrophies under many possible circumstances 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880514-0094 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the national gallery of art is mounting the 
first big show in 20 years of works by fitz hugh lane known for 
his paintings of the first winner of the americas cup and of the 
first cunard line ship to cross the atlantic 
no other painter of the 19th century matched him in capturing 
the character of maritime new england in portraying the reflective 
sheen of calm water or the agitated surface of windblown waves the 
clarity of lightfilled still air or the moist atmosphere of cloudy 
humid days gallery director j carter brown says in a tribute 
appearing in the catalogue of the exhibit 
john wilmerding the museums deputy director and a specialist 
on lane classes him just below the painter winslow homer 
lane painted the americas cup race at least twice once in an 
unusual work that contains three views of the same yacht that one 
is in the peabody museum on salem mass 
the other painting lent to this show shows the finale of the 
first race in 1851 with britons waving their hats from a smaller 
boat while the americans look the other way a british sidewheeler 
packed with spectators is nearby 
lane painted the britannia the first cunard line ship entering 
boston harbor in 1848 eight years after its first transatlantic 
voyage 
nearly all the 61 paintings in the show are of new england 
scenes all are related to ships and the sea there is a kind of 
glowing silence about them that critics say typifies the american 
movement now called luminism 
lane died in 1865 long before the term was invented 
the exhibit opens sunday in the gallerys west building and will 
be there until sept 5 it then will move to the museum of fine 
arts in boston from oct 5 to dec 31 
the exhibit has been financed by a grant from the gte 
corporation 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

