president reagan said saturday that while 
workers should get as much warning as possible before theyre fired 
or laid off he cannot sign a trade bill requiring such 
notification because it threatens to destroy jobs 
it is unfortunate but i have no choice but to send this back 
to congress reagan said of the 1000page trade measure white 
house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the veto would occur in the 
coming week 
in his weekly radio address delivered from camp david md 
reagan zeroed in on the battle over the plantclosing section of 
the bill which is expected to become a campaign issue in the fall 
elections 
while the administration supports much of the bill it faults 
the requirement that companies notify workers at least 60 days in 
advance of layoffs or a plant shutdown 
the issue should be decided between labor and management not 
government reagan argued 
let me state very clearly i believe businesses should give 
workers and communities just as much warning as they can when it 
looks as though layoffs or plant closings are going to become 
unavoidable reagan said its the humane thing to do 
but when big government gets in the middle of something like 
this dictating all its rules and regulations the humane way has a 
way of becoming inhumane reagan said 
the president contended that the requirement would force 
struggling businesses to shut down at crucial times and that 
management needs the flexibility of using temporary layoffs to get 
a business back on its feet it would also keep companies from 
adding workers if it would subject them to the bills requirements 
the president said 
although there are exceptions in the bill for companies that 
find themselves in serious financial trouble but reagan derided 
them as too vague and unclear to be workable 
reagan argued that one independent study showed that if the 
