<TEXT>
burj indiapakistan border ap as night falls on the rugged 
frontier the rattle of guns of indian border guards serves as a 
warning to potential sikh infiltrators and arms merchants who try 
to cross into india from pakistan 
the guards take target practice 500 yards from the frontier to 
warm up for the nightlong vigil 
in the past eight weeks at least 56 people have died in 47 
encounters between indian border security force and wouldbe 
infiltrators or arms smugglers 
the days of the war game are over we are faced with a 
situation where we must stop infiltration from pakistan by any 
means border force inspector general parkash singh said at the 
burj border post in punjab state 
india wants to close the border with fences men and strict 
vigilance 
the urgency to seal the 348mile section of border in punjab 
stems from escalating violence in the state where hundreds of 
people have died in sikh separatist violence this year 
sikh militants have been fighting since 1982 for an independent 
sikh homeland in punjab 
indias border with pakistan stretches 1836 miles running 
through the indian states of kashmir punjab rajasthan and gujarat 
it is a nervous border 
both nations station military forces in nearby garrisons in 
memory of the three wars they have fought in the last 41 years 
it is like firecrackers strewn all over the place what is 
needed is just a matchstick to start fullscale confrontation a 
border official told journalists who were taken to the border on a 
government tour for foreign news organizations he spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
the sikh terrorist campaign has prompted the indian government 
to take drastic steps india has accused pakistan of sheltering and 
arming the sikhs charges repeatedly denied by pakistan 
an estimated 15000 indian border guards are deployed along the 
punjab sector of the frontier 
in addition 40000 indian army men are garrisoned in punjab 
subject to callup on two hours notice 
reporters saw indian foot patrols in full combat readiness at 
burj 26 miles west of the sikh holy city of amritsar at a nearby 
100foot high observation tower two guards were looking through 
binoculars and keeping their foot patrols informed about movement 
on the pakistani side 
after sundown the tower guards use nightvision devises 
whenever a potential infiltrator is spotted the patrols are 
alerted they first ask the wouldbe infiltrators to stop and 
identify themselves 
we give them a oneminute response time if they try to run or 
fail to respond we fire said vijendra singh sirohi the border 
forces deputy inspector general for the punjab sector 
in an effort to stop infiltration the indian government has 
started fencing vulnerable sections with barbed wire 
senior officers in charge of border operations and intelligence 
say sikh violence can only be contained if infiltration from 
pakistan is checked 
the oxygen for the sikh terrorists is coming from pakistan if 
we can stop the oxygen supply terrorism will die said saran 
prasad chief of operations at the border forces headquarters in 
new delhi 
before we would have hesitated to name pakistan but now it is 
as clear as daylight i mean their help to terrorists prasad 
said 
reporters were shown arms and ammunition the officers said were 
captured from infiltrators 
the weapons included rocketpropelled grenade launchers 
sovietdesigned ak47 rifles and pistols 
it is the ak47 that worries us the most prasad said 
the border security force has nothing to match the ak47 whose 
firepower and light weight make it an ideal weapon for untrained 
gunmen 
border troops are equipped with singleshot rifles in addition 
to light machine guns that must be mounted before firing 
