<TEXT>
cocaine and communism have dominated us relations 
with latin america this decade while the regions festering 
economic and political problems are being neglected experts warn 
in an 84page report issued here 
miami report ii was prepared by bankers oil executives 
clergymen and academics led by ambler moss former us ambassador 
to panama it follows up on the groups first report in 1984 which 
accurately forecast a gradually worsening economic crisis in latin 
america 
without a solution there will be severe erosion of fragile 
democracies in latin america moss said in an interview friday 
he is now dean of the university of miami graduate school of 
international studies you cant run a democracy when the economy 
is going to hell he said 
since the early 1980s money has steadily flowed out of latin 
america to the united states depriving the underdeveloped nations 
of desperately needed capital says the study which was released 
friday by the end of 1987 latin america was staggering under a 
debt burden of 460 billion 
the authors say the region is mired in its worst depression 
since the 1930s 
argentinas elected president raul alfonsin who has had to put 
down attempted military coups frequently warns the united states 
that his regions economic troubles threaten its political 
stability 
but us policy has ignored the deeper problems concentrating 
instead on battling communism in central america moss said 
there has been almost an obssession with nicaragua to the 
exclusion of everything else moss said in the absolute worst 
case we could send troops into nicaragua but we cant send them 
into every country in latin america 
the other dominant theme in uslatin relations has been 
narcotics trafficking says university of miami professor bruce 
bagley who specializes in international relations and prepared the 
miami report ii section on drug trafficking he pointed to the 
inability of the united states to either unseat or prosecute 
panamas gen manuel antonio noriega on drug charges 
our argument is that there are many other problems equally 
fundamental bagley said in a separate interview friday by 
failing to deal with these problems the noriegas of the world can 
flourish 
even in fighting the traffickers the reagan administration has 
failed to come up with concrete antidrug aid to financially 
strapped countries or with programs to cut us demand bagley 
said 
but cocaine rhetoric and gettough policies instead of deeper 
economic issues dominate us relations with the bahamas 
jamaica mexico panama colombia peru and bolivia he said 
this is a lost decade for democracy and development in latin 
america bagley said 
the report acknowledges it is timed for the 1988 presidential 
elections and calls on us voters to demand more substance in the 
candidates latin america policy 
a section of the report by msgr bryan walsh of the miami roman 
catholic archdiocese also calls for a more realistic immigration 
policy criticizing the government for narrowing its definition of 
political asylum to thwart latin and caribbean immigrants 
miami report iis main focus is economic however and the 
authors offer what they say are moderate policies to curb the 
departure of capital from the region 
they call for latin american nations themselves to adopt 
internal policies that reassure investors moss noted that 
argentina with a foreign debt of 53 billion has flight 
capital of 39 billion deposited outside the country by 
argentines worried about the nations political and economic health 
but us policy or lack of it takes a large share of the 
blame the report says and must be changed 
one suggestion is for the us treasury to lower interest rates 
on loans made directly to smaller countries 
another is for the united states to increase funding available 
for latin america through the interamerican development bank 
