<TEXT>
university of illinois landscape architects 
are working on designs to help the government of india attract more 
tourists to key buddhist religious sites 
university officials will go to india this summer to present 
plans for redeveloping sarnath where buddha delivered his first 
sermon more than 2500 years ago 
it gives our students handson experience and it is an 
exciting challenge to develop tourism there said vincent 
bellafiore head of the universitys department of landscape 
architecture people can see a totally different religion and 
culture 
sarnath in the northern part of india contains landmark 
structures such as a temple a museum and architectural ruins but 
there also are mud houses cycle rickshaws and streets lined with 
vendors selling everything from silk to peanuts 
one goal for the university team was to create designs that suit 
both religious and recreational activities at sarnath and would cut 
down conflicts between the two 
some people come for religious devotion said bellafiore 
others picnic on the grass next to the temple with a 
ghettoblaster and barbecue meat and that is very offensive 
so the illinois students and faculty visited sarnath and 
returned with pictures and ideas then spent months on campus early 
this year developing plans for improving the site 
graduate student miki stuebe concentrated on the zoo creating 
more natural settings for animals in place of the small cages now 
used for example one of her drawings depicts an island for the 
zoos monkeys 
we want to tie into buddhist concepts like compassion for all 
living things she said 
one alternative in the plan calls for moving the zoo away from 
the key religious area 
richard blumeweaver another graduate student rolled out a 
drawing of proposed new footpaths intended to keep people from 
walking on the architectural ruins 
around some buddhist structures the plans show two paths one 
for religious pilgrims who spend much more time there and another 
for tourists who want to walk past more quickly 
in other areas of sarnath the plans along a main road include 
trees more typical of those found during buddhas time concepts 
for touristrelated market spaces and hedges to restrict the 
movement of farm animals into the site 
for overnight tourists there are concepts for new housing 
designed to blend in with the architecture of the current village 
we dont want a chichi resort in the midst of abject 
poverty said bellafiore who hopes the housing will be decorated 
with pottery and weavings by village craftsmen to help the local 
economy 
the us national park service and indias ministry of tourism 
agreed on this project the only cost was transportation and food 
and lodging in india for the university team said bellafiore 
bellafiore said he will return to india with other university 
officials to deliver the designs that will provide the indian 
government with alternatives that are not enormously expensive 
i think our plans will satisfy indias goal to increase 
tourism said blumeweaver id also like to see the ruins 
better preserved and id like to see the place respected more as a 
religious site 
similar designs may be developed by the illinois team for other 
buddhist sites in india 
