parked near reviewing stands to be used for ceremonies marking the 
withdrawal of soviet troops eleven afghans including a baby were 
killed 
residents said three rockets later hit a village on the 
outskirts of kabul killing four people and wounding four others 
the official soviet news agency tass put the death toll at three 
tass monitored in moscow blamed both attacks on afghan 
guerrillas and said one of those responsible for the 545 am 
truck attack was arrested 
soviet communist party central committee official vladimir 
sevruk reported that 11 people were killed and 12 injured in the 
explosion 
the blast killed a baby and an 11yearold girl and all the 
casualties were afghan civilians according to a western 
photographer on the scene 
most appeared to have been occupants of nearby homes destroyed 
by the impact of the explosion he said 
when the bomb exploded some of the houses nearby just 
collapsed said the photographer 
the blast was so great that it shattered the windows of a bus 
depot across the river 300 yards away and left a crater 20 feet 
wide and 10 feet deep 
soviet troops arrived afterward the photographer said by 
telephone 
the blast demolished embankment walls on both sides of the river 
that threads through this ancient capital 
blood was visible on the gates of a nearby factory and personal 
belongings including carpet slippers were scattered in the street 
the bomb had been planted in a large truck that lay badly 
mangled at the scene 
last month six people were killed and 49 wounded in another 
bomb blast along the river on the 10th anniversary of the april 
1978 revolution that brought a marxist government to power in 
afghanistan and triggered widespread insurrection 
tass said the rockets saturday hit the village of chamane 
baraqi killing an old man and two children residents said one 
rocket hit a hut killing two children inside and that an elderly 
man and another child were killed by debris the village is located 
about a halfmile from the british embassy 
at a news conference for foreign journalists who gathered for 
the beginning of the soviet withdrawal afghan president najib said 
his government will survive because it offers peace he added that 
he will address the un special session on disarmament in new york 
next month and planned trips to czechoslovakia and cuba 
we can state confidently that we will last because we strive 
and struggle for peace he said our opponents offer the afghan 
people war and the people hate this 
also at a news conference saturday the head of the soviet 
military contingent in afghanistan said the anticommunist rebels 
were taking their toll on the soviet and afghan troops but that 
rebel attacks will not deter the withdrawal which begins sunday 
the opposition may have some effect on us but not much and 
certainly they will not be able to frustrate the timetable lt 
gen boris gromov told reporters we have the means at our 
disposal to fulfill the timetable 
the comments by gromov and najib and the report of the rocket 
attack were carried in a reuters news agency pool report from 
kabul the associated press was excluded from the pool because of 
questions it asked afghan president najib last month 
under an accord signed in geneva on april 14 the soviets will 
complete their withdrawal within nine months half of the soviets 
must be out by aug 15 according to the peace agreement 
soviet soldiers entered the war in december 1979 to help the 
allied government fight off the insurgents and about 115000 
remain here to back forces loyal to president najib 
