<TEXT>
soviet dissident natan sharansky recalls in a 
new book how he forced kgb agents out of his building and into the 
cold in moscow in 1974 by threatening to call the police 
it is one of the lighter moments in sharanskys book fear no 
evil excerpted in the may 23 issue of us news amp world report 
in the years before his arrest in 1977 on suspicion of passing 
secrets to the cia sharansky was a prominent dissident who had 
been repeatedly refused permission to emigrate from the soviet 
union 
he was often followed by the kgb and says he sometimes found 
them a source of amusement he says the most fun he had at the 
kgbs expense was on nov 7 1974 a soviet holiday when sharansky 
had been assigned to work at the institute for oil and gas to take 
care of emergencies 
three tails followed me to work but because no outsiders were 
allowed in our building they had to remain in the car a little 
later the security guard called from downstairs to report that a 
group of men had come into the lobby to warm up sharansky said 
he called the kgb identified himself and said he was in charge 
of the building that day 
downstairs in the lobby are three kgb men who are following 
citizen sharansky did you give them permission to enter 
there was a long pause sharansky said and the voice asked his 
identity 
sharansky he replied 
youre making fun of us its only noon and youre already 
drunk the voice said and hung up 
sharansky said he called the building security guard and ordered 
him to tell the three men he had spoken to their boss who didnt 
approve of their being in the building 
if they dont leave ill notify the police sharansky 
said 
he said he walked to the window later and saw they were back in 
the car 
i always treasured that moment that wonderful feeling of 
having the kgb obey me he writes 
sharansky was convicted by a soviet court in 1978 of being a 
spy he was freed in february 1986 in an eastwest prisoner 
exchange and joined his wife in israel 
the magazine is scheduled to publish additional excerpts in next 
weeks issue in which sharansky details his 90 months in soviet 
prisons and a labor camp 
