<TEXT>
voters here may become the first in 
the nation to shut down an operating nuclear power plant when they 
consider rival ballot measures to decide the fate of the 
problemplagued rancho seco plant 
a measure sponsored by a group called safe or sacramentans for 
safe energy would order the permanent closure of the 14yearold 
plant one of the few publicly owned nuclear power plants in the 
country 
an alternative plan put on the june 7 ballot by the sacramento 
municipal utility district which owns rancho seco in effect asks 
the districts voters to give the the plant 25 miles southeast of 
here another chance 
the utility district which comprises sacramento and surrounding 
areas with a combined population of more than 420000 has 
struggled with operating problems at the plant for years 
in addition district consumers have struggled with electricity 
rates that have gone up nearly 85 percent in three years and 
critics blame rancho seco for that too 
the thing has such a history of running so poorly and being 
unsafe that no one would believe it wont do the same thing in the 
future said bob mulholland political director of campaign 
california an environmental and consumers group working on the 
shutdown effort 
we figure that the odds of rancho seco operating above the 
industry average are about the same as winning the california 
lottery said karl ory of campaign california 
rancho seco managers say the plant deserves another chance 
were champing at the bit to show the public we can do it 
said steve redeker deputy operations manager for the first 
time we have an attitude of do it right 
ed smeloff the only one of the five utility district board 
members who wants to shut down rancho seco said passage of the 
measure could indirectly influence the private utilities that own 
the vast majority of the nations nuclear plants even though those 
utilities are not under the control of the voters as the 
sacramento utility is they are sensitive to public opinion he 
said 
it certainly does i think set a tone if a local electorate 
doesnt want a nuclear plant he said it would worry other 
utilities across the country even if the electorate doesnt have 
the final say 
the plant built for 375 million by babcock and wilcox inc 
has a reactor design like that of three mile island reactor no 2 
the site of the nations worst commercial nuclear power plant 
accident in march 1979 
from the day of its dedication in october 1974 the plant has 
been plagued by malfunctioning equipment and operator errors that 
forced more than 100 outages including a shutdown that lasted from 
december 1985 to last month 
the nuclear regulatory commission called the overcooling 
accident that led to that shutdown one of the dozen worst problems 
suffered by us plants in 1985 
the agency gives the plant one of the worst efficiency ratings 
of any in the nation federal investigations have concluded that 
the plant had a history of mismanagement poor or nonexistent 
maintenance poor operator training inattention to detail and 
failure to learn from past mistakes 
a federal investigation of a 1985 overcooling accident also 
found that an important monitor was set at a level that would 
underestimate escaping radiation 
proponents of the shutdown dubbed measure b on the ballot 
include mayor anne rudin and a majority of the sacramento city 
council they argue that the plant will never be adequate or 
reliable and will require an endless stream of money for scheduled 
modifications and unforeseen repairs 
proponents of the alternate measure measure c argue that the 
utility has spent 400 million to overhaul the plant is hiring an 
outside company to manage it and deserves a chance to prove rancho 
secos viability but the proposed hiring of another manager has 
provoked another dispute because the company duke power co of 
north carolina contributed 100000 to the measure c campaign 
measure c includes a provision that would call for the district 
to shut down rancho seco any time after dec 31 if the plant fails 
to operate at more than 50 percent of capacity for four consecutive 
months 
in the past the plant has managed to operate at an average of 
just 40 percent of capacity the 50 percent requirement however 
could be overridden by four of the utilitys five directors 
opponents of the plant question how legally binding measure c 
would be 
its my legal opinion that measure c in no way restricts the 
board from doing anything they want said attorney michael remy 
safe chairman whatever voters decide on june 7 the issue will 
almost certainly end up in court remy said 
</TEXT>
