<TEXT>
washington was talking last week about two 
things what donald regan said and whether he should have said it 
beyond the spate of jokes produced by his revelations about mrs 
reagans fascination with astrology and the presidents passive 
management style there arose a debate over the ethics of 
kissandtell books 
if you want to contribute to history it wont hurt to wait 
until the administration is over said sheila tate mrs reagans 
former spokeswoman 
but george e reedy former press secretary to president lyndon 
b johnson said administration figures should be able to tell 
their stories whenever they wish 
speech in this country is free says reedy who teaches 
journalism ethics at marquette university unless those people 
had agreed that they would not do anything like this i cant see 
it as being unethical 
regans book for the record from wall street to 
washington is a biting account that some feel weakens an already 
lameduck presidency he portrays a choeographed president 
manipulated by aides and by a wife who depends on an astrologist 
for guidance in fixing the presidents schedule 
president reagan has denounced the book as a bunch of 
falsehoods and a breach of confidence but not given a 
detailed rebuttal 
being kissed by the heady power of the white house and then 
publicly telling the story especially when the president still 
sits in the oval office is to some dishonorable to others a 
valuable contribution to history 
the presidents former chief of staff ousted from the white 
house last year in a move widely believed engineered by mrs 
reagan says he never considered delaying his tale 
i didnt set the time of my leaving this administration and i 
dont know why i should hold up many people have left this 
administration and told their stories why not my book he said 
in an interview 
his is one of several negative accounts by former reagan 
officials 
former white house spokesman larry speakes offered damaging 
characterizations of former colleagues in his book speaking 
out he says he may have overstepped the bounds of propriety in 
some instances but addes i apologize not for the truth in my 
book nor the telling of it 
david stockman reagans former budget director caused a furor 
two years ago with the triumph of politics why the reagan 
revolution failed which lays out errors in judgment and 
miscalculations stockman says were responsible for adding 1 
trillion to the national debt 
i wrote the book because i have an ax to grind he said 
then and to correct a gigantic mishap of governance 
ironically one of those who warned stockman against being too 
candid was regan then treasury secretary 
just why the reaganera books have been so angry and revealing 
is a provocative question 
reedy says he has never encountered books as violent as 
those spawned by the reagan presidency and adds there is 
obviously something in that white house that is filling people with 
a sense of rage 
mrs tate the first ladys former spokeswoman dismisses that 
theory 
this is not a problem peculiar to the reagan administration 
she says theres big money being offered and staff have become 
more powerful its the cult of the personality a lot of people 
who worked in the white house in the 50s were nameless and 
faceless in the 80s they have highprofile jobs that bring a lot 
of personal attention to them 
james david barber a duke university political science 
professor who studies presidential character notes that the reagan 
books have a remarkable consistency in the picture they convey of 
this white house 
where is the book that overwhelmingly corrects these 
supposedly false and unjust smear jobs that straightens it all 
out that shows that the president was really in charge he asks 
he believes such books help citizens learn how policymakers do 
their jobs and whether their values are right 
that thought is echoed by historian arthur schlesinger jr who 
says these memoirs are a venerable genre in american political 
literature that should not be withheld 
how else can history be written if those who make it take vows 
of silence he said 
samuel kernell a political science professor at the university 
of california at san diego who is studying the white house staff 
says the proliferation of such books reflects the growth of the 
white house and the centralization of power in unknown people 
making vital decisions 
he notes that the white house staff has grown from about 40 
people in 1939 to nearly 500 today those people have tremendous 
influence on american policy so were naturally curious about 
them thats why they get on the cover of time magazine and why 
their books are marketable 
on the other hand telling how an administration operates while 
it is still operating can put a damper on administration programs 
the proposition that there even are going to be kissandtell 
books does erode the sense of collegiality within government 
says stephen hess a brookings institution scholar who served on 
the eisenhower and nixon staffs and has studied the presidency and 
the press 
if you sit there at a table and you know that everybody is 
going to run back and write in their diary it will affect what you 
can say and how you say it hess says it becomes simply an 
ethical consideration based on each persons moral code whether 
theyre going to tell tales out of school it tells you something 
about those people 
some have suggested presidents ask incoming aides to sign a 
promise not to write until later 
what ever happened to the first amendment regan says in 
response dont we have as much right to write i could see if 
that applied to state secrets but i dont describe how to make an 
atomic bomb 
jody powell president carters press secretary who wrote a book 
targeting the washington press corps says he promised his 
administration colleagues they werent ever going to have to see 
their topofthehead statements and analyses tossed back at them 
years later in one of his books 
powell says the promise was his idea and was not put into any 
formal agreement many feel such agreements probably unforceable 
in any case would only underscore an atmosphere of distrust 
there may always be people who put loyalty to the president 
behind the prospect of financial gain celebrity status or avenging 
some real or imagined slight 
presidents get what they deserve they either generate a sense 
of loyalty among the members of their staff or they dont says 
reedy 
regan bristles at the notion that he has been disloyal and 
recalls how he was hounded out of my office loyalty he says 
is a twoway proposition 
in the end says regan i could either write this book and 
tell the whole truth or not write the book at all i chose to write 
the book 
</TEXT>
